If a server is compromised, the hacker's malware usually tries to reach back out to their command-and-control server over the internet.

ss -tulpn: This looks terrifying, but it is a SOC Analyst's favorite command. It lists all active network connections and open ports on the machine.

-t = TCP connections

-u = UDP connections

-l = Listening ports

-p = Shows the process name using the port

-n = Shows numeric IP addresses instead of names

SOC Application: If you see an unknown external IP address connected to your server on a random port, you are looking at a live data exfiltration attempt.
